What the contract does:
Stores a password as a public string variable set at deployment. Has an authenticate() function that compares a submitted passkey against the stored password using keccak256 hashing. Sets a cleared boolean to true if they match.
The vulnerability:
The password is declared as a public state variable. Anyone can call contract.password() directly and retrieve it, bypassing the intended authentication entirely.
How I exploited it:
Called await contract.password() to retrieve the plaintext password ("ethernaut0"), then submitted it via await contract.authenticate("ethernaut0").
